---
import SchemaLayout from '../../../layouts/SchemaLayout.astro';
import drugsData from '../../../../data/drugs.json';

const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;

// Drugs requiring renal dose adjustment
const renalAdjDrugs = (drugsData as any[])
  .filter(d => d.renal_dose_adjustment)
  .map(d => ({
    id: d.id,
    name: d.generic_name,
    drugClass: d.drug_class,
    excretion: d.pharmacokinetics?.excretion || '—',
    halfLife: d.pharmacokinetics?.half_life || '—',
    ismpHighAlert: d.ismp_high_alert,
  }))
  .sort((a, b) => a.name.localeCompare(b.name));

// Drugs NOT requiring renal dose adjustment (primarily hepatic)
const hepaticPrimary = (drugsData as any[])
  .filter(d => !d.renal_dose_adjustment && d.hepatic_dose_adjustment)
  .map(d => ({
    id: d.id,
    name: d.generic_name,
    drugClass: d.drug_class,
    excretion: d.pharmacokinetics?.excretion || '—',
  }))
  .sort((a, b) => a.name.localeCompare(b.name));

// TDM drugs
const tdmDrugs = (drugsData as any[]).filter(d => d.tdm_required);

// Dialyzable drugs (look for dialyz keywords in excretion)
const dialyzable = (drugsData as any[]).filter(d => {
  const ex = (d.pharmacokinetics?.excretion || '').toLowerCase();
  return ex.includes('dialyz') || ex.includes('hemodialysis') || ex.includes('hd ');
});

// Non-dialyzable
const nonDialyzable = (drugsData as any[]).filter(d => {
  const ex = (d.pharmacokinetics?.excretion || '').toLowerCase();
  return ex.includes('not dialyz') || ex.includes('non-dialyz') || ex.includes('not removed by');
});

// Renally cleared unchanged (no hepatic metabolism)
const renalUnchanged = (drugsData as any[]).filter(d => {
  const met = (d.pharmacokinetics?.metabolism || '').toLowerCase();
  const ex = (d.pharmacokinetics?.excretion || '').toLowerCase();
  return (met.includes('not hepatically') || met.includes('not metabolized') || met.includes('minimal hepatic') ||
          met.includes('excreted unchanged') || ex.includes('excreted unchanged'));
});
---
<SchemaLayout
  title="Excretion — ADME Schema"
  schema="adme"
  description="Renal clearance, dose adjustment in CKD, hepatic/biliary excretion, and dialyzability."
>
  <div class="mb-6">
    <div class="breadcrumbs text-sm mb-4">
      <ul>
        <li><a href={`${base}schemas/06-adme/`} class="link link-hover">ADME</a></li>
        <li>Excretion</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <h1 class="text-4xl font-serif font-bold mb-2">Excretion</h1>
    <p class="text-base-content/70 text-lg">Renal clearance, CKD dose adjustment, and dialyzability</p>
  </div>

  <div class="prose max-w-none mb-10">
    <p>
      Drug excretion is the irreversible removal of drug and its metabolites from the body,
      occurring predominantly through the kidneys and secondarily through biliary secretion
      into the gastrointestinal tract. Renal excretion involves three distinct processes:
      glomerular filtration, which passively filters unbound drug across the glomerular
      basement membrane at a rate determined by the glomerular filtration rate (GFR) and
      the free drug fraction; tubular secretion, an active transporter-mediated process
      in the proximal tubule that can concentrate drugs in the tubular lumen far above
      plasma concentrations, accounting for the rapid elimination of penicillins,
      thiazides, loop diuretics, and metformin; and tubular reabsorption, which reclaims
      lipophilic, non-ionized drug from the tubular lumen back into the bloodstream
      according to concentration gradients. Urinary pH profoundly influences reabsorption
      of ionizable drugs: acidification of urine traps basic drugs in their ionized,
      membrane-impermeant form (exploited therapeutically to enhance amphetamine and
      phencyclidine excretion in overdose), while alkalinization traps acidic drugs
      such as salicylates and phenobarbital (used in alkaline diuresis for aspirin
      toxicity). The clinical estimation of renal function for drug dosing purposes
      uses the Cockcroft-Gault equation to estimate creatinine clearance (CrCl),
      which most pharmacokinetic studies used to establish dose adjustment thresholds;
      the CKD-EPI equation is superior for classifying CKD stage but CrCl remains
      the standard for dose adjustment calculations.
    </p>
    <p>
      Renal impairment reduces drug clearance in proportion to the kidney's contribution
      to total body clearance, potentially leading to drug and metabolite accumulation,
      toxicity, and adverse effects at doses that would be safe in renally intact patients.
      The clinical severity of renal impairment for any drug depends on two factors: the
      fraction of the drug eliminated unchanged by the kidney (fe), and the drug's
      therapeutic index. Drugs eliminated primarily by the kidney with narrow therapeutic
      indices — vancomycin, aminoglycosides, digoxin, lithium, metformin, and enoxaparin —
      require the most careful dose adjustment in CKD and are associated with the greatest
      risk of toxicity when impairment goes unrecognized. Of the {drugsData.length} drugs
      in this reference database, {renalAdjDrugs.length} ({Math.round(renalAdjDrugs.length/drugsData.length*100)}%)
      require renal dose adjustment. The mechanism of toxicity in renal impairment varies
      by drug: metformin accumulation causes lactic acidosis; methotrexate accumulation
      causes mucositis and myelosuppression; vancomycin accumulation causes nephrotoxicity
      and ototoxicity; fluoroquinolones accumulate and lower the seizure threshold. The
      nurse must confirm current renal function before administering renally-cleared drugs,
      verify that the dose ordered accounts for the patient's CrCl, and monitor for early
      signs of accumulation-related toxicity.
    </p>
    <p>
      Biliary excretion and enterohepatic recirculation represent important but underappreciated
      excretion pathways for selected drug classes. Drugs actively secreted into bile by
      hepatic transporters (BCRP, MRP2, P-gp) are delivered to the small intestine where
      they may be excreted in feces or, if deconjugated by gut bacteria, reabsorbed and
      recycled through the portal circulation — a process called enterohepatic recirculation
      that prolongs drug half-life and maintains plasma concentrations beyond what hepatic
      metabolism alone would predict. Cholestyramine and activated charcoal can interrupt
      enterohepatic recirculation by binding drug in the gut lumen before reabsorption,
      accelerating elimination — a principle exploited in the management of leflunomide
      toxicity (cholestyramine washout procedure) and some oral overdoses. Biliary
      excretion is the dominant elimination route for certain lipophilic antibiotics
      (ceftriaxone, rifampin, azithromycin), making them effective for biliary infections
      but also responsible for concentration-dependent biliary sludging and
      pseudolithiasis observed with high-dose ceftriaxone in neonates.
    </p>
    <p>
      Dialyzability — the extent to which hemodialysis or peritoneal dialysis can remove
      a drug — is clinically critical in two situations: (1) when a dialysis patient is
      prescribed a regularly dosed drug and supplemental post-dialysis doses may be
      required to maintain therapeutic concentrations, and (2) when a patient presents
      with drug toxicity and dialysis is considered to accelerate drug removal. Three
      pharmacokinetic properties determine dialyzability: low molecular weight (below
      500–1000 Da), low plasma protein binding, and low volume of distribution
      (indicating the drug resides predominantly in plasma rather than tissues).
      Drugs meeting all three criteria — lithium, metformin, phenobarbital,
      theophylline, salicylates, aminoglycosides, and valacyclovir — are effectively
      removed by hemodialysis. Drugs with large volumes of distribution
      (digoxin, amiodarone, tricyclic antidepressants), high protein binding
      (warfarin, valproate, diazepam), or high molecular weight (vancomycin,
      though high-flux dialyzers are more effective) are poorly removed by
      conventional dialysis. In patients on hemodialysis receiving dialyzable
      drugs, the nurse must verify whether a supplemental post-dialysis dose
      is prescribed, as dialysis can reduce plasma concentrations below therapeutic
      thresholds for antibiotics such as aminoglycosides and vancomycin.
    </p>
  </div>

  <!-- Stats -->
  <div class="stats stats-horizontal shadow w-full mb-8 flex-wrap">
    <div class="stat">
      <div class="stat-title">Renal Dose Adjustment</div>
      <div class="stat-value text-amber-600">{renalAdjDrugs.length}</div>
      <div class="stat-desc">drugs require CKD adjustment</div>
    </div>
    <div class="stat">
      <div class="stat-title">Renally Cleared Unchanged</div>
      <div class="stat-value text-amber-600">{renalUnchanged.length}</div>
      <div class="stat-desc">no hepatic metabolism</div>
    </div>
    <div class="stat">
      <div class="stat-title">TDM Required</div>
      <div class="stat-value text-amber-600">{tdmDrugs.length}</div>
      <div class="stat-desc">therapeutic drug monitoring</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- TDM Table -->
  <h2 class="text-2xl font-serif font-bold mb-3">Therapeutic Drug Monitoring (TDM) — Renally Relevant</h2>
  <p class="text-sm text-base-content/70 mb-4">
    {tdmDrugs.length} drugs require plasma concentration monitoring. For renally-cleared TDM drugs,
    CKD requires both dose adjustment AND more frequent TDM due to unpredictable accumulation.
  </p>
  <div class="overflow-x-auto mb-8">
    <table class="table table-zebra table-sm w-full">
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Drug</th>
          <th>Class</th>
          <th>Renal Adj. Required</th>
          <th>Excretion Notes</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        {tdmDrugs.map((d: any) => (
          <tr>
            <td><a href={`${base}drugs/${d.id}/`} class="link link-hover font-medium capitalize">{d.generic_name}</a></td>
            <td class="text-xs text-base-content/70">{d.drug_class}</td>
            <td>
              {d.renal_dose_adjustment
                ? <span class="badge badge-error badge-sm">Yes</span>
                : <span class="badge badge-ghost badge-sm">No</span>
              }
            </td>
            <td class="text-xs max-w-xs truncate" title={d.pharmacokinetics?.excretion}>
              {d.pharmacokinetics?.excretion || '—'}
            </td>
          </tr>
        ))}
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <!-- Renally cleared unchanged -->
  <h2 class="text-2xl font-serif font-bold mb-3">Drugs Excreted Renally Unchanged</h2>
  <p class="text-sm text-base-content/70 mb-4">
    These {renalUnchanged.length} drugs are not significantly metabolized hepatically and are
    excreted primarily as unchanged drug in urine. They are most susceptible to accumulation in CKD.
  </p>
  <div class="flex flex-wrap gap-1 mb-8">
    {renalUnchanged.map((d: any) => (
      <a href={`${base}drugs/${d.id}/`} class={`badge badge-sm link link-hover capitalize ${d.ismp_high_alert ? 'badge-error' : d.renal_dose_adjustment ? 'badge-warning' : 'badge-outline'}`}>
        {d.generic_name}
      </a>
    ))}
  </div>

  <!-- Full renal adjustment table -->
  <h2 class="text-2xl font-serif font-bold mb-3">All Drugs Requiring Renal Dose Adjustment ({renalAdjDrugs.length})</h2>
  <div class="alert alert-warning mb-4">
    <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" class="stroke-current shrink-0 h-5 w-5" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M12 9v2m0 4h.01m-6.938 4h13.856c1.54 0 2.502-1.667 1.732-3L13.732 4c-.77-1.333-2.694-1.333-3.464 0L3.34 16c-.77 1.333.192 3 1.732 3z" /></svg>
    <div class="text-sm">
      <strong>Nursing Priority:</strong> Before administering any drug flagged below, confirm current serum creatinine
      or eGFR/CrCl is documented and the ordered dose accounts for renal function.
      High-alert drugs (<span class="badge badge-error badge-xs">HA</span>) require extra verification.
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="overflow-x-auto mb-10">
    <table class="table table-zebra table-pin-rows table-sm w-full">
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Drug</th>
          <th>Class</th>
          <th>High Alert</th>
          <th>Half-Life</th>
          <th>Excretion / Dose Adjustment Notes</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        {renalAdjDrugs.map((drug) => (
          <tr>
            <td>
              <a href={`${base}drugs/${drug.id}/`} class="link link-hover font-medium capitalize">
                {drug.name}
              </a>
            </td>
            <td class="text-xs text-base-content/70">{drug.drugClass}</td>
            <td>
              {drug.ismpHighAlert && <span class="badge badge-error badge-sm">HA</span>}
            </td>
            <td class="text-xs font-mono">{drug.halfLife}</td>
            <td class="text-xs max-w-sm truncate" title={drug.excretion}>{drug.excretion}</td>
          </tr>
        ))}
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <!-- Dialyzability -->
  <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 mb-10">
    <div class="card bg-base-100 shadow">
      <div class="card-body">
        <h3 class="card-title text-success">Dialyzable Drugs</h3>
        <p class="text-xs text-base-content/70 mb-2">
          {dialyzable.length} drugs removed by hemodialysis. Supplemental post-HD doses may be required.
        </p>
        <div class="flex flex-wrap gap-1">
          {dialyzable.map((d: any) => (
            <a href={`${base}drugs/${d.id}/`} class="badge badge-success badge-sm link link-hover capitalize">{d.generic_name}</a>
          ))}
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="card bg-base-100 shadow">
      <div class="card-body">
        <h3 class="card-title text-error">Non-Dialyzable / Poor Removal</h3>
        <p class="text-xs text-base-content/70 mb-2">
          {nonDialyzable.length} drugs not effectively removed by dialysis (high Vd or protein binding).
          Dialysis will NOT expedite drug removal in overdose.
        </p>
        <div class="flex flex-wrap gap-1">
          {nonDialyzable.map((d: any) => (
            <a href={`${base}drugs/${d.id}/`} class="badge badge-error badge-sm link link-hover capitalize">{d.generic_name}</a>
          ))}
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="divider my-8"></div>
  <div class="flex gap-4 justify-between text-sm">
    <a href={`${base}schemas/06-adme/cyp-metabolism/`} class="btn btn-outline btn-sm">← CYP Metabolism</a>
    <a href={`${base}schemas/06-adme/special-populations/`} class="btn btn-primary btn-sm">Special Populations →</a>
  </div>
</SchemaLayout>
